description.text:
### Description

For simple setups, where only Zettlr without external Pandoc or TEX is installed, the simple PDF export functionality is crucial. However, it currently does not work as a WYSIWYG export: some elements, that are rendered in the Zettlr UI are not rendered accordingly in the Export.

The simple PDF export works by first exporting to HTML and then using the embedded Browser to print. We can customize the HTML template so solve some of the shortcomings mentioned above, e.g. we could render mermaid diagrams using mermaid.js. However, the print trigger unfortunately does not await JavaScript execution.

### Proposed Changes

To overcome that, Zettlr should wait for some DOM events instead of just calling webContents.printToPDF() in its electron backend (I assume in [pdf-exporter.ts](https://github.com/Zettlr/Zettlr/blob/48277f249e4b613e3d8d1abf9aa828b754ccdadc/source/app/service-providers/commands/exporter/pdf-exporter.ts#L62)).

A simple Template for better out-of-the-box exports to HTML and PDF could look as follows. Note, that this works well if exported to HTML and then manually printed to PDF. It however does not work because of the described behaviour if using Export simple PDF (pdf-simple) in Zettlr directly:

```
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>$title$</title>
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
  <style>
    body {
      font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
      margin: 0;
      padding: 2em;
      background-color: #f9f9f9;
      display: flex;
      justify-content: center;
    }
    .page {
      background-color: white;
      padding: 20mm 20mm 30mm 20mm;
      box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);
      max-width: 21cm;
      width: 100%;
      position: relative;
      min-height: 100vh;
      box-sizing: border-box;
    }
    img {
      max-width: 100%;
      padding-bottom: 1em;
      padding-top: 1em;
    }
    section:not(:has(section)) {
      page-break-inside: avoid;
    }
    p, div {
      page-break-inside: avoid;
    }
    @media print {
      body {
        background-color: white;
        margin: 0;
        padding: 0;
        display: block;
      }
      .page {
        box-shadow: none;
        padding: 0mm 20mm 0mm 20mm;
        margin: 0;
        width: auto;
        max-width: none;
      }
      .header-space {
        margin-top: 10mm;
      }
      .footer-space {
        margin-bottom: 10mm;
      }
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <table>
    <!-- thead and tfoot are the only elements that get repeated accross pages on browser initiated page breaks -->
    <thead><tr><td>
      <div class="header-space">&nbsp;</div>
    </td></tr></thead>
    <tbody><tr><td>
      <div class="page">
        $body$
      </div>
    </td></tr></tbody>
    <tfoot><tr><td>
      <div class="footer-space">&nbsp;</div>
    </td></tr></tfoot>
  </table>
  <script type="module">
    import mermaid from 'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/mermaid@10/dist/mermaid.esm.min.mjs';
    mermaid.initialize({ startOnLoad: false }); // prevents a defect pdf export.

    window.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", () => {
      document.querySelectorAll("pre.mermaid").forEach(pre => {
        const code = pre.querySelector("code");
        if (code) {
          pre.innerHTML = code.textContent;
        }
      });

      // render manually; this works in html export, however lets the output of mermaid code in pdf intact.
      // this could be avoided by setting initialize:startOnLoad=true, if Zettlr would avait javascript
      // execution on page load, bevore chromium freezes the page for printing
      async function renderMermaid() {
        const mermaidBlocks = document.querySelectorAll('pre.mermaid');

        for (const block of mermaidBlocks) {
          const code = block.textContent;
          try {
            const { svg } = await mermaid.render('mermaid-' + Math.random().toString(36).substr(2, 9), code);
            const container = document.createElement('div');
            container.innerHTML = svg;
            block.replaceWith(container);
          } catch (err) {
            console.warn('Mermaid rendering failed:', err);
          }
        }
      }
      renderMermaid();
   });
</script>

  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

The template can easily be added to the HTML export Asset:
```
...
standalone: true
template: path/to/zettlr/defaults/custom-template.html
...
```

### Caveats

The proposed solution could impose a security risk, if an attacker is able to introduce arbitrary javascript in Zettlr templates. However, if an attacker is able to to so on a local machine, he might have more interesting possibilities than that...

### Do you Wish to Attempt Implementing this Yourself?

No

### Zettlr Version

Stable (most recent version)

